<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Speed Trap<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.71)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10269'>Steve "Saintmaker" Wagner</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10269&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 2, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> If you have played the card game, Mille Bournes, then you will see the resemblance between the two. You are trying to reach your destination, 1000 miles or kilometers, whatever the French use, and your best way of doing it, most games, is to stop the opponent any way you can. Since it was a driving game, the way you did it was making his car stop moving some how, either by flat tires, engine problems, an accident, or even the cursed red light. All did the job. Usually if stopped enough, a player will have no chance of recovery.<br>
Where is the connection in LotR? Most of the time, players are looking to get to site 9 faster than the opponent does. It is the most successful and usual way to win. Some decks are able to kill their opponent a large percentage of the times, but they are still not a guaranteed thing.<br>
When building decks, most players look at Fellowship cards that will make their decks go faster than the other players do. They also look for things, at the least, will slow their opponent enough that the &#39;race&#39; will not be much of a race. <br>
Most of the fellowship side of decks, however, is strong enough these days to run. They may not run every time, but given the chance, and with a good (or bad) enough draw, you may find yourself behind even if you went first.<br>
So I decided to look for a way to slow down the opponent&#39;s deck, but with more than good minions and damage dealing. Sometimes that doesn&#39;t always do the trick. You need back-up and here is my one or two extra card back-up plan. You may have to tailor your deck around them. But it might be the one small difference of winning the race.<br>
Have you seen the cards that say &#39;do this or have this in play,&#39; and your opponent has -1 move. Think about that for a moment. If in a 2 player game, you can move up to maximum of 2 sites a turn, you have just cut your opponent&#39;s move into half. If you are a site ahead of him, barring any miracles (or Sleeps) he cannot outrun you. And if he is ahead just by one, you can overtake him with a single double move. <br>
Let&#39;s look at the cards that have this ability. The one that says &#39;I have less uses than manure,&#39; is a Sauron card called The Number Must Be Few. It says spot 7 companions, to make the move -1. Furthermore, it costs 2 twilight. How many games have you seen 7 companions out? Not very many, I bet. It&#39;s not useless, but I would still avoid it.<br>
Another Sauron card, called Sauron&#39;s Defenses, is a much better deal, although at first glance it doesn&#39;t seem that way. It says that your opponent has to have 3 or more companions in the dead pile. Seem tough? A little, yes. But with the Hate/ Bowmen/ Watching Eye decks, it&#39;s not as tough as you think. You should get that many companions dead before then, especially if they are using weaker ones. You could even put it in any other deck that kills companions, as long as you have a Sauron Orc to exert for it. <br>
The last card is the best, in my eyes, and can be easily fulfilled with the right cards. It needs quite a few cards dedicated to it, but they are not expensive, and do other things besides fulfilling the condition. A Saruman card, Traitor&#39;s Voice, says that you need one of 2 things to get the -1 move. Either 5 burdens (very possible in the game these days) or an exhausted Ring bearer. That one isn&#39;t as tough as you think, either. Not with Witch-Kings (MoM) and Ulaire Enquea (MoM) running amuck, dealing damage to the ring bearer if they win their skirmishes. But the ultimate card to use, without even leaving the Saruman culture, is Worry, the card that doesn&#39;t seem to be as good as it really is. Either way you win with Worry. Thanks to this combination, I&#39;ve corrupted a Ring bearer with Worry twice, something I could never do if the move limit wasn&#39;t reduced.<br>
So instead of racing so fast that you lose control, try throwing some speed blocks in front of your opponent. It will be a much safer, better trip for you, and a headache for him or her.    <br>
 <br>
-I will put the decks at a later time, if there is enough interest in them.<br>
